{{Taxobox | color = violet | name = Cydia pomonella granulovirus | virus_group = i | ordo = ''Unassigned'' | familia = ''[[Baculoviridae]]'' | genus = ''[[Betabaculovirus]]'' | species = '''''Cydia pomonella granulovirus''''' }}
'''Cydia pomonella granulovirus (CpGV)''' is a [[granulovirus]] belonging to the family ''[[Baculoviridae]]''.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=International Committee on Taxonomy of Viruses |title=ICTV 2015 Master Species List Version 1 |date=June 2016 |url=https://talk.ictvonline.org/files/master-species-lists/m/msl/5945}}</ref> It has a double-stranded DNA genome that is 123,500 base pairs in length with 143 [[Open reading frame|ORF]]s.<ref name=Luque>{{cite journal |title=The complete sequence of the ''Cydia pomonella'' granulovirus genome |year=2001 |last1=Luque |first1=T. |last2=Finch |first2=R. |last3=Crook |first3=N. |last4=O'Reilly |first4=D.R. |last5=Winstanley |first5=D. | journal=Journal of General Virology |volume=82 |pages=2531–47 |pmid=11562546 |doi=10.1099/0022-1317-82-10-2531}}</ref> The virus forms small bodies called granules containing a single virion. CpGV is a virus of invertebrates – specifically ''[[Codling moth|Cydia pomonella]]'', commonly known as the Codling moth.<ref name=Tanada>{{cite journal |title=A granulosis virus of the codling moth, Carpocapsa pomonella (Linnaeus) (Olethreutidae, Lepidoptera) |year=1964 |last1=Tanada |first1=Y. |journal=Journal of Insect Pathology |volume=6 |pages=378–380 }}</ref> CpGV is highly pathogenic, it is known as a fast GV – that is, one that will kill its host in the same [[instar]] as infection; thus, it is frequently used as a [[biological pesticide]].
==CpGV in pest control== ''C. pomonella'' has proved to be a problematic pest on several fruit trees, including apples and pears. The caterpillars burrow into the fruit, rendering it unfit for sale. Traditional insecticides are of limited use, as some strains have acquired resistance to several insecticides.
CpGV has been shown to kill many of the larvae of ''C. pomonella'' in trials without having adverse effects on humans or other animals, thanks to the specific nature of the virus. Also, no development of resistance was observed.{{citation needed|reason=Please provide a source for these trials|date=June 2016}}
The first CpGV strain, isolated in Mexico, has been commercially formulated into biological pesticides such as Madex (Andermatt Biocontrol AG), Carpovirusine (NPP/Arysta LifeScience) and Cyd-X (Certis).<ref name=Tanada/><ref name=Knox>{{cite journal |doi=10.1080/09583157.2014.949222 |title=Baculovirus-based strategies for the management of insect pests: a focus on development and application in South Africa |year=2015 |last1=Knox |first1=C.M. |last2=Moore |first2=S.D. |last3=Luke |first3=G.A. |last4=Hill |first4=M.P. |journal=Biocontrol Science and Technology |volume=25 |number=1 |pages=1–20 }}</ref> Due to the continued use of CpGV in the field, populations resistant to the Mexican strain of ''C. pomonella'' have been identified.<ref name=Schmitt>{{cite journal |title=The occurrence and distribution of resistance of codling moth to ''Cydia pomonella'' granulovirus in Europe |year=2013 |last1=Schmitt |first1=A.B. |last2=Ladurner |first2=I.L. |last3=Benuzzi |first3=M. |last4=Sauphanor |first4=B. |last5=Kienzle |first5=J. |last6=Zingg |first6=D. |last7=Undorf-Spahn |first7=K. |last8=Fritsch |first8=E. |last9=Huber |first9=J. |last10=Jehle |first10=J.A. | journal=Journal of Applied Entomology |volume=137 |issue=9 |pages=641–9 |doi=10.1111/jen.12046}}</ref> New strains which are able to manage resistant codling moth populations have been developed. These strains are commercialized by NPP/Arysta LifeScience into Carpovirusine Evo 2 and by Andermatt Biocontrol AG into Madex Max and Madex Plus.
