'''Meredith Perry''' (1991−)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/2015/02/23/ubeam-founder-meredith-perry-replaces-cords-with-wireless-charging/23699083/|title=The inventor who may kill the power cord|work=USA TODAY|access-date=2018-07-30|language=en}}</ref> is an American entrepreneur and the founder of [[uBeam]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ubeam.com/|title=ubeam {{!}} Wireless Power|website=www.ubeam.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-07-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://patents.justia.com/inventor/meredith-perry|title=Meredith Perry Inventions, Patents and Patent Applications - Justia Patents Search|website=patents.justia.com|language=en|access-date=2018-07-30}}</ref>

Perry attended the [[University of Pennsylvania]] (2007–2011) and graduated with a degree in Paleobiology, Geology, Astrobiology. She presented the uBeam at the universities "PennVention", an invention competition, and the uBeam won.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crunchbase.com/organization/ubeam#/entity|title=uBeam {{!}} Crunchbase|website=Crunchbase|language=en|access-date=2018-07-30}}</ref> Later, she presented her design at the All Things Digital conference in 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://patents.justia.com/inventor/meredith-perry|title=Meredith Perry Inventions, Patents and Patent Applications - Justia Patents Search|website=patents.justia.com|language=en|access-date=2018-07-30}}</ref> Perry was a student ambassador at [[NASA]] Ames Research Center  where she led a zero gravity experiment, worked on technology to discover life on Mars, and researched astrobiology and medicine.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/2011/08/23/139854129/young-entrepreneur-has-a-better-idea-now-what|title=Young Entrepreneur Has A Better Idea. Now What?|work=NPR.org|access-date=2018-07-30|language=en}}</ref>

== uBeam ==

The uBeam device emits a high frequency sounds (inaudible to human ears) and transmits power directly to receivers, thus enabling users to walk around the room, laptop in hand without needing to be physically stationed to a charging location (like WIFI for charging).<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://fortune.com/2014/12/30/meredith-perry-ubeam/|title=She's an inventor. She's 25. And she wants to make true wireless charging a reality|work=Fortune|access-date=2018-07-30|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/08/18/technology/an-inventor-wants-one-less-wire-to-worry-about.html|title=An Inventor Wants One Less Wire to Worry About|last=Hitt|first=Jack|access-date=2018-07-30|language=en}}</ref>  The effectiveness and safety of the technology have been questioned.<ref>{{cite web |title=Wireless Charging: uBeam’s Headache and Nausea Question |url=http://observer.com/2015/11/ubeam-questions-headache-nausea-hearing-loss/ |website=Observer |date=9 November 2015}}</ref>

uBeam has received over $26 million<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/news/2017/06/01/ubeams-meredith-perry-shows-her-stealth-wireless-charging-technology-really-works/102336880/|title=uBeam's Meredith Perry shows her stealth wireless charging technology really works|work=USA TODAY|access-date=2018-07-30|language=en}}</ref> in investments from [[Mark Cuban]], [[Marissa Mayer]], [[Andreessen Horowitz]], [[Shawn Fanning]],<ref name=":3">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/bizjournals/news/2015/02/10/upstart100-meredith-perry.html|title=Meredith Perry — uBeam|website=www.bizjournals.com|access-date=2018-07-30}}</ref>  Zappos’s CEO [[Tony Hsieh]], Peter Thiel's [[Founders Fund|Founder's Fund]], among others.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://makeitinla.org/podcast/meredith-perry-ubeam/|title=MAKE IT IN LA {{!}} Meredith Perry: uBeam|website=MAKE IT IN LA|language=en-US|access-date=2018-07-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/2015/02/23/ubeam-founder-meredith-perry-replaces-cords-with-wireless-charging/23699083/|title=The inventor who may kill the power cord|work=USA TODAY|access-date=2018-07-30|language=en}}</ref><ref name=":1">{{Cite news|url=https://www.fastcompany.com/3029523/meredith-perry|title=Meredith Perry|date=2014-05-12|work=Fast Company|access-date=2018-07-30|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=":2">{{Cite news|url=http://fortune.com/2012/10/11/more-under-40s-mobilizers/|title=More under 40s: Mobilizers|work=Fortune|access-date=2018-07-30|language=en}}</ref>

